Feature: BC session-start treats a locally-writable-but-unpushable work-tracker as unhealthy and hard-blocks all role-work from starting

  Per the stakeholder decision (Brief 010 §3), "healthy" requires a proven remote
  round-trip: a test dolt push to the configured Dolt remote must succeed. This
  scenario pins that criterion as its own behavior: a tracker that accepts local
  writes (bd create / bd ready succeed) but whose test dolt push FAILS is
  UNHEALTHY. The BC must then HARD-BLOCK ALL role-work AT STARTUP — it does not
  begin its role loop and does not emit any role work — and surface an explicit,
  actionable failure naming the failed remote push. This catches the latent
  fault where work proceeds and issues accrue locally but are unrecoverable
  downstream because the tracker can never push. (lead-80t0; Brief 010 §3
  test-dolt-push criterion.)

  @scenario_hash:43a05feaefc1d046
  Scenario: a BC session starts with a locally-writable tracker whose test dolt push fails and the health step blocks all role-work from starting
    Given a BC shop whose bd tracker has a definite issue_prefix configured and a populated working set
    And bd create and bd ready run in the BC shop both exit zero
    And the tracker has a configured Dolt remote
    And a test dolt push to the configured Dolt remote exits non-zero
    When the BC agent session starts and runs the work-tracker health step
    Then the health step reports the tracker as unhealthy and names the failed test dolt push as the cause
    And the BC does not begin its role loop
    And the BC emits no role work
    And the failure is surfaced at session-start rather than at work_done emission
